# Project: Jest JavaScript/TypeScript Unit Testing Framework

## Framework Structure
- Use Jest as the primary test runner for JavaScript and TypeScript projects
- Configure Jest via jest.config.js (or jest.config.ts) at the project root
- Use ts-jest or Babel for TypeScript transformation
- Organize tests alongside source files (*.test.ts) or in dedicated __tests__ directories
- Keep test helper utilities and shared fixtures in a __tests__/helpers or __tests__/fixtures directory

## Coding Standards
- Follow JavaScript/TypeScript best practices and project ESLint rules
- Use TypeScript for type-safe test implementations when the source is TypeScript
- Use meaningful test and variable naming that reads like a sentence
- Limit describe block nesting to 3 levels maximum
- Keep each test file focused on a single module or unit of behavior

## Test Organization
- Group related tests using describe blocks named after the unit under test
- Use it() or test() for individual test cases; prefer it() for readability ("it should...")
- Use beforeEach/afterEach for per-test setup and teardown
- Use beforeAll/afterAll only for expensive shared setup that is truly read-only
- Separate unit, integration, and component tests into distinct directories or Jest projects

## Best Practices
- Follow Arrange-Act-Assert (AAA) pattern with blank lines separating each section
- Write focused, single-responsibility tests — one logical assertion per test
- Avoid test interdependencies; each test must be runnable in isolation
- Never share mutable state across tests via module-level variables
- Use jest.isolateModules() when you need clean module registry per test
- Prefer explicit expectations over snapshot-only tests for critical logic

## Mocking Strategies
- Use jest.fn() for simple function mocks; provide implementation via mockImplementation()
- Use jest.mock('<module>') for module-level mocking at the top of the test file
- Use jest.spyOn(object, 'method') to spy on or override real implementations
- Restore mocks after each test with jest.restoreAllMocks() in afterEach or via restoreMocks: true in config
- Use jest.useFakeTimers() for time-dependent tests (setTimeout, setInterval, Date)
- Mock HTTP requests with msw (Mock Service Worker) for realistic fetch/axios interception
- Use jest.resetModules() in beforeEach when module state must be fresh per test

## Assertions
- Use expect() with specific, descriptive matchers rather than generic truthy/falsy checks
- Prefer toEqual() for deep equality over toBe() for objects and arrays
- Use toThrow() / toThrowError() for error path assertions; always wrap in an arrow function
- Use toHaveBeenCalledWith() over toHaveBeenCalled() to assert exact arguments
- Implement custom matchers via expect.extend() for domain-specific assertions
- Use expect.assertions(n) in async tests to guard against missed await keywords

## Async Testing
- Always use async/await for asynchronous tests; never return bare Promises
- Use waitFor() from Testing Library for UI state changes instead of arbitrary timeouts
- Combine jest.useFakeTimers() with jest.runAllTimers() or jest.advanceTimersByTime() for timer tests
- Handle unhandled promise rejections by asserting with rejects: await expect(promise).rejects.toThrow()

## Coverage
- Configure coverage with the v8 provider (preferred) or babel/istanbul
- Set meaningful coverage thresholds in jest.config.js under coverageThreshold
- Use collectCoverageFrom to target only production source files, excluding generated code
- Generate lcov and text-summary reporters for CI and local visualization
- Upload coverage reports to services like Codecov or SonarQube in CI pipelines

## Performance
- Run test suites in parallel by default (Jest's default behavior); avoid --runInBand except for debugging
- Use --shard for splitting large test suites across CI workers
- Minimize heavy setup in beforeAll; prefer lightweight beforeEach setup
- Use jest.mock() to avoid real I/O (network, filesystem, database) in unit tests
- Enable cacheDirectory in jest.config.js to speed up repeated runs locally

## Component Testing
- Use @testing-library/react (or /vue, /svelte, /angular) for user-centric DOM assertions
- Query elements by accessible roles, labels, and text — avoid querying by class or id
- Use userEvent from @testing-library/user-event over fireEvent for realistic browser interactions
- Wrap components in required providers (Router, Store, Theme) using a custom render helper
- Use screen.debug() and prettyDOM() during development, not in committed tests

## Snapshot Testing
- Use toMatchSnapshot() only for stable, presentational components where the full output is meaningful
- Prefer toMatchInlineSnapshot() for small, critical output to keep context visible in the test file
- Always review and commit snapshot changes deliberately; treat a diff as a real assertion failure
- Run jest --updateSnapshot only after manually verifying the new output is correct

## Test Data Management
- Use factory functions or a builder pattern for reusable test data objects
- Define TypeScript interfaces or types for all test data structures
- Avoid hardcoded magic values; use named constants or factory defaults
- Generate dynamic or random test data with @faker-js/faker when needed
- Store shared fixtures in __tests__/fixtures and import explicitly — do not rely on global setup for data

## CI/CD Integration
- Use --ci flag in CI environments to fail on missing snapshots instead of creating them
- Configure --reporters=default,jest-junit for CI pipeline compatibility
- Enable --forceExit to prevent Jest from hanging if async resources are not cleaned up
- Cache the Jest cache directory and node_modules between CI runs for speed
- Run jest --coverage only on CI or as a pre-commit gate, not on every watch-mode run

## Environment Configuration
- Set testEnvironment to node (default) for server-side code or jsdom for browser/DOM code
- Configure moduleNameMapper for path aliases and static asset stubs (images, CSS modules)
- Use setupFilesAfterFramework (setupFilesAfterFramework: ['<rootDir>/jest.setup.ts']) for global test setup
- Handle environment variables with dotenv-jest or by setting process.env in jest.config.js
- Use projects array in jest.config.js to run multiple configurations (e.g., unit + integration) in one command

## Error Handling
- Test both success and failure code paths for every public function
- Assert on specific error messages and types, not just that an error was thrown
- Use expect().rejects.toThrow() for async error assertions
- Verify that cleanup logic runs even when errors occur (e.g., resources are released in finally blocks)

## Documentation
- Name test files to mirror the source file: src/utils/format.ts → src/utils/format.test.ts
- Write test descriptions that serve as living documentation of expected behavior
- Document non-obvious mock setups with a brief inline comment explaining why the mock is needed
- Maintain a README in the __tests__ directory describing test categories, how to run them, and coverage goals

Remember to leverage Jest's rich ecosystem — ts-jest, jest-extended, msw, and Testing Library — for robust, maintainable JavaScript and TypeScript unit tests.
